*************************** T H E O R Y **************************2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
TALYS is a computer code system for the prediction and analysis   2043 1451
of nuclear reactions. TALYS simulates reactions that involve      2043 1451
neutrons, gamma-rays, protons, deuterons, tritons, helions and    2043 1451
alpha-particles, in the 1 keV - 200 MeV energy range and for      2043 1451
target nuclides of mass 12 and heavier. This is achieved by       2043 1451
implementing a suite of nuclear reaction models into a single     2043 1451
code system. It enables to evaluate nuclear reactions from        2043 1451
the unresolved resonance region up to intermediate energies. This 2043 1451
evaluation is based on a theoretical analysis that utilizes the   2043 1451
optical model, compound nucleus statistical theory, direct        2043 1451
reactions and pre-equilibrium processes, in combination with      2043 1451
databases and models for nuclear structure. For Ca-46, the        2043 1451
following output of TALYS is stored in this data file:            2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
- Total, elastic and non-elastic cross sections                   2043 1451
- Elastic scattering angular distributions                        2043 1451
- Inelastic cross sections to discrete states                     2043 1451
- Inelastic scattering angular distributions to discrete states   2043 1451
- Exclusive channel cross sections, e.g. (n,g), (n,2n), (n,np),.. 2043 1451
- Exclusive channel energy spectra                                2043 1451
- Exclusive channel double-differential spectra                   2043 1451
- Exclusive gamma production for discrete states and continuum    2043 1451
- Isomeric and ground state cross sections                        2043 1451
- Residual production cross sections                              2043 1451
- Total particle cross sections, e.g. (n,xn), (n,xp),..           2043 1451
- Total particle energy spectra                                   2043 1451
- Total particle double-differential spectra                      2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
Here follows a short description of the used nuclear models:      2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
##### OPTICAL MODEL                                               2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
All optical model calculations are performed by ECIS-97 [ray94],  2043 1451
in TALYS used as a subroutine. The default optical model          2043 1451
potentials (OMP) used are the local and global parameterizations  2043 1451
of Koning and Delaroche [kon03]. These are phenomenological OMPs  2043 1451
for neutrons and protons which in principle are valid over the    2043 1451
1 keV - 200 MeV energy range, though the low energy boundary of   2043 1451
validity may differ from nucleus to nucleus (e.g. for the total   2043 1451
cross sections, experimental data are included directly in the    2043 1451
file for energies below that boundary). Solving the Schroedinger  2043 1451
equation with this OMP yields the total cross section, the        2043 1451
shape-elastic cross section, the shape-elastic angular            2043 1451
distribution, the wave functions for the direct reaction cross    2043 1451
sections (see below), the transmission coefficients for the       2043 1451
compound nucleus model (see below) and the reaction cross         2043 1451
sections for the pre-equilibrium model (see below).               2043 1451
For neutrons and protons, the used parameterization is given in   2043 1451
Eq. (7) of [kon03].                                               2043 1451
To calculate the transmission coefficients and reaction cross     2043 1451
sections for deuterons, tritons, helions and alpha particles, we  2043 1451
use OMPs that are directly derived from our nucleon potentials    2043 1451
using Watanabe's folding approach [mad88].                        2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
##### DIRECT REACTIONS                                            2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
The built-in ECIS-97 is used for coupled-channels or DWBA         2043 1451
calculations for rotational or vibrational (or a combination of   2043 1451
these) nuclides. For Ca-46, DWBA was used to compute the direct   2043 1451
cross sections to several low-lying discrete levels:              2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
Level   Energy  Spin/Parity   Deformation parameter beta_l        2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
   1   1.346000   2.0+          0.153                             2043 1451
   6   3.614000   3.0-          0.204                             2043 1451
 + a few additional states with small deformation parameters.     2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
In addition, a macroscopic, phenomenological model to describe    2043 1451
giant resonances in the inelastic channel is used. For each       2043 1451
multipolarity an energy weighted sum rule applies and a DWBA      2043 1451
calculation with ECIS-97 is performed for each giant resonance    2043 1451
state. The cross section is then spread over the continuum with a 2043 1451
Gaussian distribution.                                            2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
##### COMPOUND NUCLEUS                                            2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
For binary compound nucleus reactions we use the model of         2043 1451
Moldauer [mol80], i.e. the Hauser-Feshbach model [hau52]          2043 1451
corrected for width fluctuations. The transmission coefficients   2043 1451
have been generated with the aforementioned OMPs and the full     2043 1451
j,l-dependence of the transmission coefficients in the            2043 1451
Hauser-Feshbach model is used. For each nucleus that can be       2043 1451
reached through a binary reaction, several discrete levels and a  2043 1451
continuum described by level densities are included               2043 1451
simultaneously as competing channels.                             2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
The compound nucleus angular distributions are calculated with    2043 1451
the Blatt-Biedenharn formalism [bla52], leading to compound       2043 1451
nucleus Legendre coefficients that are added to their direct      2043 1451
counterparts. For multiple compound emission, i.e. emitted        2043 1451
particles after the binary emission, we use the Hauser-Feshbach   2043 1451
model. Again, for each residual nucleus several discrete states   2043 1451
are included as well as a continuum described by level densities. 2043 1451
Multiple compound emission is continued until all reaction        2043 1451
channels are closed and the population distribution of all        2043 1451
residual nuclides is depleted, through gamma decay, until they    2043 1451
end up in the ground state or in an isomer.                       2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
For the level density, we take the composite formula proposed by  2043 1451
Gilbert and Cameron [gil65], consisting of a constant temperature 2043 1451
law at low energies and a Fermi gas expression at high energies.  2043 1451
For the level density parameter a we use the energy dependent     2043 1451
expression proposed by Ignatyuk [ign75] to take into account the  2043 1451
damping of shell effects at high excitation energy. We have       2043 1451
obtained the parameters for the Ignatyuk formula from a           2043 1451
simultaneous fit to all experimental D_0 values as present in the 2043 1451
RIPL library. If necessary, we adjust individual parameters to    2043 1451
obtain a better fit to experiment.                                2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
Gamma-ray transmission coefficients are generated with the        2043 1451
Kopecky-Uhl generalized Lorentzian for strength                   2043 1451
functions [kop90], with giant dipole resonance parameters taken   2043 1451
from the RIPL library [rip98], and normalized with experimental   2043 1451
radiative widths [gar84].                                         2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
##### PRE-EQUILIBRIUM REACTIONS                                   2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
For pre-equilibrium reactions, which become important for         2043 1451
incident energies above about 10 MeV, we use the two-component    2043 1451
exciton model [kon04b], in which the neutron or proton types of   2043 1451
particles and holes are followed throughout the reaction. For     2043 1451
energies above 20 MeV, multiple pre-equilibrium emission up to    2043 1451
any order of particle emission was included in the calculations.  2043 1451
A parameterization for the squared matrix element is used that is 2043 1451
valid for the whole energy range of this evaluation.              2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
For deuterons, tritons, helions and alpha-particles, an extra     2043 1451
contribution was added from the pick/up and knock-out reaction    2043 1451
model by Kalbach [kal01].                                         2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
For photons, the model of Akkermans and Gruppelaar [akk85] was    2043 1451
applied, to simulate the direct and semi-direct capture           2043 1451
processes.                                                        2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
The angular distribution systematics by Kalbach [kal88] were used 2043 1451
to describe the angular distributions for all continuum           2043 1451
particles. An isotopic distribution for photons was adopted.      2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
****** C O M P A R I S O N    W I T H    E X P E R I M E N T *****2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
This evaluation was performed simultaneously with other adjacent  2043 1451
isotopes, both for incident neutrons and protons. This enables,   2043 1451
when compared with a single-isotope effort, to put stronger       2043 1451
constraints on the produced calculated data, i.e. a globally      2043 1451
good comparison between TALYS and experimental data is requested  2043 1451
for all isotopes at the same time, while nucleus-specific input   2043 1451
(default or adjusted) parameters are consistently used for all    2043 1451
isotopes. Also, experimental data that is not available for the   2043 1451
isotope under study may be present, and tested, for adjacent      2043 1451
nuclides or for other projectiles. If these can be successfully   2043 1451
described by the models, a similar performance can be expected    2043 1451
for the present data file.                                        2043 1451
A few level density parameters for residual nuclides have been    2043 1451
adjusted to enforce agreement with the experimental data. The     2043 1451
changes in the level density parameters, a, were all kept within  2043 1451
10% of their default values.                                      2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
##### TOTAL AND REACTION CROSS SECTIONS AND ELASTIC SCATTERING    2043 1451
                                                                  2043 1451
The spherical OMP was tested against experimental data for total  2043 1451
cross sections and elastic scattering angular distributions.      2043 1451
Consult [kon03] for the complete experimental database and for a  2043 1451
comparison of calculations and measurements over the whole energy 2043 1451
range for natural Ca.                                             2043 1451
